        <h1>LeetCode 1611: Minimum One Bit Operations to Make Integers Zero (C++)</h1>

        <div class="problem-description">
            <p><strong>Problem:</strong>
                Given an integer n, you must transform it into 0 using the following operations any number of times: (1) Change the rightmost (0th) bit in the binary representation of n. (2) Change the ith bit in the binary representation of n if the (i-1)th bit is set to 1 and the (i-2)th through 0th bits are set to 0. Return the minimum number of operations to transform n into 0.
            </p>
            <p><strong>Example:</strong>
                Input: n = 3<br>
                Output: 2<br>
                Explanation: Binary representation of 3 is "11". "11" → "01" with the 2nd operation. "01" → "00" with the 1st operation.
            </p>
        </div>

        <div class="code-container">
            <button class="copy-button" onclick="copyCode(this)">Copy Code</button>
            <pre><code class="language-cpp">class Solution {
public:
    int minimumOneBitOperations(int n) {
        // This problem is related to Gray Code
        // The answer is to convert n to its Gray code inverse
        // Gray code inverse formula: XOR all bits from MSB
        
        int result = 0;
        
        while (n &gt; 0) {
            result ^= n;
            n &gt;&gt;= 1;
        }
        
        return result;
    }
};</code></pre>
